# Ch3 in book

# Plant Cells
- Eukaryotic cells, plantae
- Plastids, can perform [[Unsorted/Photosynthesis\|photosynthesis]] and store starch
- Vacuole to regulate turgor pressure (water)
- No flagella or centrioles, except in gametes
- Unique cell division method
	- Form cell plate AKA phragmoplast, separates cells 

## Cell structure

![Pasted image 20220829113935.png](data:image/png;base64,)

- Cell structure
	- Cell wall
		- ![Pasted image 20220829115056.png](data:image/png;base64,)
		- Distinct to plant cells
		- Contain cellulose, hemicelluloses, and pectin
		- Surrounds the cytoplasma
		- Mechanically protects against osmotic stress, provides tensile strength
		- Lets cells develop turgor pressure
			- > Higher pressure than animal cells?
		- Intracellular connections called plasmodesmata
			- Narrow thread of cytoplasm that passes through cell walls
			- It's how cells exchange resources and communicate
			- Also how pathogens spread
			- ![Pasted image 20220829115044.png](data:image/png;base64,)
	- Plastids (chloroplasts?)
		- Includes chloroplasts, chromoplasts, lecuoplasts
		- Photosynthesize
		- Store starch
		- Membrane-bound endosymbiotic organisms
	- Vacuoles
		- Regulate turgor pressure
		- Store and move resources
	- Phragmoplast
		- Structure inside plant cells during [[cytokinesis\|cytokinesis]]
		- Framework for cell plate assembly
		- Made of microtubules, actin, 
		- Why cuttings from plants are able to grow
	- Parenchyma
		- The cells that produce resources through [[Unsorted/Photosynthesis\|photosynthesis]]
			- Leaves are primarily composed of these
		- Stores food and nutrients
		- Support and foundation
		- Involved in growth
		- Site of ALL metabolic activities
		- Helps regenerate, repair wounds
	- Collenchymal cells
		- Provide FLEXIBLE structural support
	- Schlerenchymal cells
		- Very thick walls that provide suport
